did.abstract: The William Hugh Jansen papers (dated 1938-1979; 26 cubic feet; 89 boxes) include correspondence, notes, folklore related materials, and student projects amassed during his career as a professor at the University of Kentucky.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The William Hugh Jansen papers (dated 1938-1979; 26 cubic feet; 89 boxes) include correspondence, notes, folklore related materials, and student projects amassed during his career as a professor at the University of Kentucky. The collection also contains personal research materials dating prior to Dr. Jansen's arrival at the University of Kentucky in 1949. The greater part of the collection is made up of materials acquired by Jansen in the years he taught as a member of the English Department at UK.

separatedmaterial.head: Separated Materials
separatedmaterial.p: All student records, including grades, and letters of recommendation, have been removed as they violated the FERPA Act.

accessrestrict.head: Conditions Governing Access
accessrestrict.p: The collection is open to researchers by appointment.

userestrict.head: Conditions Governing Use
userestrict.p: The intellectual rights to the materials in this collection are held by the University of Kentucky Special Collections and Digital Programs with the exception of student papers. According to section 106 of the Copyright Law a student owns any and all rights in and to the works they create as part of their educational experiences. This does include any work a student creates within the scope of any particular class she/he takes. Use of the student materials in this collection requires consent from the student.

prefercite.head: Preferred Citation
prefercite.p: 2000ua146: [identification of item], William Hugh Jansen papers, 1938-1979, University of Kentucky Special Collections.

bioghist.head: Biographical note
bioghist.p: William Hugh Jansen received the third Doctorate in Folklore in the United States from the Indiana University. He was a member of the faculty of the University of Kentucky English Department from 1949-1979. Jansen became internationally known for his work on cultural stereotyping. He published fifty articles, and served as an editor of four state and regional folklore journals. He was a Fellow of the American Folklore society, a Fulbright Lecturer, a Ford Foundation Fellow, a Fellow of the National Endowment for the Humanities, a member of the International Society of Folk Narrative Research, and a delegate to the International Council of Learned Societies.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: The collection is arranged into five series and thirteen subseries by subject.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The student materials series contains ungraded materials produced by students of William Hugh Jansen. The bulk of the series consist of student papers and index cards of collected folklores. The folklores primarily document the Bluegrass Region of Kentucky, as well as the western and eastern parts of the state. There are a few examples of folklores collected outside of Kentucky.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: These materials are index cards of recorded folklores which were collected to satisfy the requirements of courses taught by William Hugh Jansen. The bulk of the materials are from his time as a faculty member in the English Department but some of the materials were produced during his time as a doctoral student at Indiana University. These names associated with these index cards can be found in an older collection inventory in the collection file. If there is no note associated with a box it means that it is unclear where that set of index cards fit within the old inventory.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The Correspondence series contains both professional and personal correspondence both sent and received by William Hugh Jansen throughout his career. Subjects covered include participation in professional organizations, overseas programs and projects, University of Kentucky affairs, and publications.

did.unittitle: General - includes letter from Wendell Ford
Concerning the death of Alec Helm

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This subseries contains correspondence between William Hugh Jansen and other folklorists discussing future publication of folklore materials. In many cases drafts of the publications are included with the correspondence. None of these works are by Jansen, those materials are contained in the Professional materials series. This correspondence documents how Jansen interacted with other professionals within the field of folklore.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The Professional Materials Series documents the career of William Hugh Jansen. It contains awards and achievements, international projects and committees, course mateials, participation in professional organizations, University of Kentucky affairs, folklores collected by Jansen, publications and papers, research material, and materials related to the creation of a folk archive.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The Awards and Achievements subseries contains acknowledgements of the professional achievements of William Hugh Jansen.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The International Projects and Committees subseries contains materials documenting William Hugh Jansen's role as Overseas Project Director. The majority of the materials pertain to sending students to Indonesia and Thailand. This series contains mainly correspondence between Jansen and individuals abroad who were responsible for American students studying abroad. This series also contains correspondence between Jansen and the federal government documenting the approval of these programs.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The Profession Organizations subseries contains materials about William Hugh Jansen's role in shaping professional folklore organizations, American Folklore Society, Association of Folk Festivals, and American Council of Learned Societies chief among them. Jansen also took part in international folklore societies such as the International Folklore Festival as well as regional folklore societies such as the Midwest Folklore Society

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The University of Kentucky Affairs subseries documents the activities of William Hugh Jansen in his role as a faculty member at the University of Kentucky English Department. Materials include correspondence related to committee work, his role in English language instruction, the creation of new courses in folklore and his role as an advisor. All materials related to student records have been removed in compliance with the Family Educational Rights and Privacy Act.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The Collected Folklores subseries contain materials collected by William Hugh Jansen over the course of his career. Many of these folklores were used in publication by Jansen. These materials were collected in Kentucky, Indiana, and West Virginia as well as internationally.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The Publications and Papers subseries contain both published and unpublished materials written by William Hugh Jansen. The majority of the unpublished materials stems from his time as a student. There is also early drafts of several manuscripts, most notably the Abe "Oregon" Smith manuscript.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The Folk Archive subersies documents the efforts by Jansen and others to try to establish a folk archive. The impetus for this effort was the growing concern by some folklorist that collecting folklore was not enough to enusre their survival that an archive where materials could be organized and preserved was also important.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The Audio Materials subseries contains the Everett/Edwards Folklore Cassettes, recordings from the Pine Mountain Folklore Project, recorded student folklores, and recordings of William Hugh Jansen from the radio. The Everett/Edwards folklore cassettes were meant to be a teaching tool and Jansen contributed one lecture for that series. The Pine Mountain Folklore Project was designed to intensively study the status of folklore in that eastern Kentucky community. Folklores were collected by initially going door to door in the Pine Mountain Community, and later by going to recommended homes. The result is a mixture of ballads and spoken folklores.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The Course Materials subseries contains materials documenting courses which William Hugh Jansen taught at the University of Kentucky as a member of the English Department. The bulk of the materials are from folklore courses and are syllabi, exams, and reading lists. All student materials have been removed in compliance with The Family Educational Rights and Privacy Act.
